[Student "E"]
{[showcards S:DJ W:D2 N:D4]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \HQ, you played low and North won the \HA.

North now plays the \DJ on which East plays the \D2. What do you play now, and what is your plan.

Play the \D3 and when North plays another \D win with your \DA.

South hoped his \D suit would provide enough tricks to make the game. You can see that there is no entry to the South hand EXCEPT in \Ds, so you want to win your \DA on the trick that North plays his last \D. How can you tell which trick that is?

Only by watching what East plays. On the \DJ East played the \D2, a low card signaling that he held an ODD number of \Ds. ODD must be either one or three so when he followed to the next \D you know he started with three. A little bit of counting tells you that North started with the doubleton Jack, so you want to win the second \D trick.

This defense holds North to one \D tricks, if you had let him win the second one he would have had 9 tricks. }
[Play "W"]HQ

